This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with the task of keypoint detection. Additionally, the use of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The combination of handcrafted and learned filters within a multi-scale architecture also suggests that it may belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the evaluation of the approach on a benchmark dataset suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
